<subSubSection lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="363" pageId="5" pageNumber="362" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1436,1378,2015]" pageId="5" pageNumber="362">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,267,1378,1403]" pageId="5" pageNumber="362">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[273,374,1378,1402]" class="Malacostraca" family="Epialtidae" genus="Rochinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="5" pageNumber="362" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[273,374,1378,1402]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="362">Rochinia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a large genus, with 
<number box="[623,651,1378,1402]" pageId="5" pageNumber="362" value="38.0">38</number>
recognised species from the Atlantic and Indo-West Pacific (modified from Ng 
<emphasis box="[256,314,1414,1438]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="362">et al.</emphasis>
<number box="[322,382,1414,1438]" pageId="5" pageNumber="362" value="2008.0">2008</number>
; Richer de Forges &amp; Ng 
<number box="[669,730,1414,1438]" pageId="5" pageNumber="362" value="2013.0">2013</number>
). Many authors (e.g., Ng &amp; Richer de Forges 
<number box="[1254,1314,1414,1438]" pageId="5" pageNumber="362" value="2007.0">2007</number>
; Richer de Forges &amp; Ng 
<number box="[309,368,1450,1474]" pageId="5" pageNumber="362" value="2009.0">2009</number>
a, b, 
<number box="[424,483,1450,1474]" pageId="5" pageNumber="362" value="2013.0">2013</number>
; Richer de Forges &amp; Poore 
<number box="[806,864,1450,1474]" pageId="5" pageNumber="362" value="2008.0">2008</number>
) have argued that the genus is heterogeneous, but splitting it into discrete groups has proved difficult. A precise definition for the genus has also proven to be difficult, with the diagnosis given in Griffin &amp; Tranter (
<number box="[783,844,1522,1547]" pageId="5" pageNumber="362" value="1986.0">1986</number>
: 
<number box="[856,899,1522,1546]" pageId="5" pageNumber="362" value="174.0">174</number>
) no longer accurate. In the years since, authors have removed 
<taxonomicName authority="A. Milne-Edwards, 1875" authorityName="A. Milne-Edwards" authorityYear="1875" box="[318,788,1557,1582]" class="Malacostraca" family="Epialtidae" genus="Sphenocarcinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="5" pageNumber="362" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[318,496,1558,1582]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="362">Sphenocarcinus</emphasis>
A. Milne-Edwards, 
<number box="[729,788,1557,1582]" pageId="5" pageNumber="362" value="1875.0">1875</number>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authority="Miers, 1885" authorityName="Miers" authorityYear="1885" box="[849,1155,1557,1582]" class="Malacostraca" family="Epialtidae" genus="Oxypleurodon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="5" pageNumber="362" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[849,1008,1558,1582]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="362">Oxypleurodon</emphasis>
Miers, 
<number box="[1097,1155,1557,1582]" pageId="5" pageNumber="362" value="1885.0">1885</number>
</taxonomicName>
, from its synonymy (see Richer de Forges 
<number box="[367,424,1594,1618]" pageId="5" pageNumber="362" value="2009.0">2009</number>
a for discussion); and Sakai (
<number box="[779,837,1594,1619]" pageId="5" pageNumber="362" value="1986.0">1986</number>
) established a new genus, 
<taxonomicName box="[1167,1329,1594,1617]" class="Malacostraca" family="Epialtidae" genus="Goniopugettia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="5" pageNumber="362" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1167,1329,1594,1617]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="362">Goniopugettia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, for one Japanese species. Richer de Forges &amp; Ng (
<number box="[641,700,1629,1654]" pageId="5" pageNumber="362" value="2009.0">2009</number>
b) also separated two very unusual species, 
<taxonomicName authority="Rathbun, 1916" authorityName="Rathbun" authorityYear="1916" class="Malacostraca" family="Epialtidae" genus="Rochinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="5" pageNumber="362" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nodosa">
<emphasis box="[1202,1316,1630,1654]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="362">R. nodosa</emphasis>
(Rathbun, 
<number box="[151,208,1666,1691]" pageId="5" pageNumber="362" value="1916.0">1916</number>
)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Griffin &amp; Tranter, 1986" authorityName="Griffin &amp; Tranter" authorityYear="1986" box="[270,670,1666,1691]" class="Malacostraca" family="Epialtidae" genus="Rochinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="5" pageNumber="362" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="carinata">
<emphasis box="[270,397,1667,1690]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="362">R. carinata</emphasis>
Griffin &amp; Tranter, 
<number box="[611,670,1666,1691]" pageId="5" pageNumber="362" value="1986.0">1986</number>
</taxonomicName>
, into a new genus, 
<taxonomicName box="[884,1016,1666,1690]" class="Malacostraca" family="Epialtidae" genus="Laubierinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="5" pageNumber="362" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[884,1016,1666,1690]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="362">Laubierinia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1436,1378,2015]" lastBlockId="6.[151,1436,151,1149]" lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="363" pageId="5" pageNumber="362">
Of the remaining species, several groups of 
<taxonomicName box="[690,791,1702,1726]" class="Malacostraca" family="Epialtidae" genus="Rochinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="5" pageNumber="362" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[690,791,1702,1726]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="362">Rochinia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
that can be recognised, and they can be briefly diagnosed as follows. Adults of 
<taxonomicName box="[412,513,1738,1762]" class="Malacostraca" family="Epialtidae" genus="Rochinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="5" pageNumber="362" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" sensu="stricto">
<emphasis box="[412,513,1738,1762]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="362">Rochinia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[524,588,1739,1762]" pageId="5" pageNumber="362" sensu="stricto">s. str.</taxonomicNameLabel>
(
<typeStatus box="[607,657,1738,1762]" pageId="5" pageNumber="362">type</typeStatus>
species 
<taxonomicName authority="A. Milne-Edwards, 1875" authorityName="A. Milne-Edwards" authorityYear="1875" box="[763,1214,1738,1763]" class="Malacostraca" family="Epialtidae" genus="Rochinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="5" pageNumber="362" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gracilipes">
<emphasis box="[763,911,1738,1762]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="362">R. gracilipes</emphasis>
A. Milne-Edwards, 
<number box="[1155,1214,1738,1763]" pageId="5" pageNumber="362" value="1875.0">1875</number>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authority="Thompson, 1873" authorityName="Thompson" authorityYear="1873" class="Malacostraca" family="Epialtidae" genus="Rochinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="5" pageNumber="362" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="carpenteri">
<emphasis box="[1283,1435,1739,1762]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="362">R. carpenteri</emphasis>
(Thompson, 
<number box="[293,350,1774,1798]" pageId="5" pageNumber="362" value="1873.0">1873</number>
))
</taxonomicName>
have raised and distinct carapace regions, and may be covered by large tubercles or spines with the rest of the surface smooth, the anterior male thoracic sternum is transversely broad and the male abdomen acutely triangular to T-shaped (
<figureCitation box="[518,588,1845,1870]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1823,1845]" captionTargetBox="[182,1399,193,1793]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[182,1399,193,1793]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 5. Anterior thoracic sternums and abdomens of Rochinia species. A, R. gracilipes A. Milne-Edwards, 1875, male (15.8 × 11.2 mm) (USNM 1150573), Mar del Plata at breakwater, Buenos Aires, Argentina; B, R. carpenteri (Thompson, 1873), male (41.7 × 33.9 mm) (NHM 1983.449), England; C, R. brevirostris (Doflein, 1904), male (15.8 × 11.4 mm) (ZRC 2011.1047), stn AT 89, 14 ° 59.74 ' S 166 ° 55.3 ' E, Vanuatu; D, R. pulchra (Miers, 1885), male (17.6 × 15.4 mm) (ZRC 2011.1043), stn CC 2746, 15 ° 58.78 ' N 121 ° 46.44 ' E, Luzon, Philippines; E, R. kotakae Takeda, 2001, male (13.4 × 17.2 mm) (ZRC 2011.1051), stn CP 2680, 14 ° 53.32 ' N 123 ° 14.40 ' E, Luzon, Philippines; F, R. fultoni, male (13.7 × 10.4 mm) (ZRC 2011.1057), stn CP 2832, 10 ° 44.54 ' S 162 ° 19.65 ' E, Solomon Islands." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/221767/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="362">
Fig. 
<number box="[574,588,1845,1870]" pageId="5" pageNumber="362" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
A, B). A second group has relatively distinct carapace regions, with the surfaces smooth but the lateral branchial spine is low or even absent (e.g., 
<taxonomicName authority="Doflein, 1904" authorityName="Doflein" authorityYear="1904" box="[1020,1382,1882,1907]" class="Malacostraca" family="Epialtidae" genus="Rochinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="5" pageNumber="362" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevirostris">
<emphasis box="[1020,1183,1882,1906]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="362">R. brevirostris</emphasis>
(Doflein, 
<number box="[1304,1363,1882,1906]" pageId="5" pageNumber="362" value="1904.0">1904</number>
))
</taxonomicName>
, and these species have a transversely broad male anterior thoracic sternum with a triangular or T-shaped male abdomen (
<figureCitation box="[159,226,1954,1979]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1823,1845]" captionTargetBox="[182,1399,193,1793]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[182,1399,193,1793]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 5. Anterior thoracic sternums and abdomens of Rochinia species. A, R. gracilipes A. Milne-Edwards, 1875, male (15.8 × 11.2 mm) (USNM 1150573), Mar del Plata at breakwater, Buenos Aires, Argentina; B, R. carpenteri (Thompson, 1873), male (41.7 × 33.9 mm) (NHM 1983.449), England; C, R. brevirostris (Doflein, 1904), male (15.8 × 11.4 mm) (ZRC 2011.1047), stn AT 89, 14 ° 59.74 ' S 166 ° 55.3 ' E, Vanuatu; D, R. pulchra (Miers, 1885), male (17.6 × 15.4 mm) (ZRC 2011.1043), stn CC 2746, 15 ° 58.78 ' N 121 ° 46.44 ' E, Luzon, Philippines; E, R. kotakae Takeda, 2001, male (13.4 × 17.2 mm) (ZRC 2011.1051), stn CP 2680, 14 ° 53.32 ' N 123 ° 14.40 ' E, Luzon, Philippines; F, R. fultoni, male (13.7 × 10.4 mm) (ZRC 2011.1057), stn CP 2832, 10 ° 44.54 ' S 162 ° 19.65 ' E, Solomon Islands." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/221767/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="362">
Fig. 
<number box="[212,226,1954,1979]" pageId="5" pageNumber="362" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
C). A third group contains species that have numerous sharp spines on the prominent carapace regions (e.g., 
<taxonomicName authority="Miers, 1885" authorityName="Miers" authorityYear="1885" box="[151,455,1990,2015]" class="Malacostraca" family="Epialtidae" genus="Rochinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="5" pageNumber="362" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pulchra">
<emphasis box="[151,273,1990,2014]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="362">R. pulchra</emphasis>
(Miers, 
<number box="[378,436,1990,2015]" pageId="5" pageNumber="362" value="1885.0">1885</number>
))
</taxonomicName>
, and the constituent species have relatively more transversely narrow anterior male thoracic sternum, with sternite 
<number box="[500,514,152,176]" pageId="6" pageNumber="363" value="4.0">4</number>
anteriorly constricted and their male abdomens are acutely triangular or T-shaped (
<figureCitation box="[159,228,188,213]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1823,1845]" captionTargetBox="[182,1399,193,1793]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[182,1399,193,1793]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 5. Anterior thoracic sternums and abdomens of Rochinia species. A, R. gracilipes A. Milne-Edwards, 1875, male (15.8 × 11.2 mm) (USNM 1150573), Mar del Plata at breakwater, Buenos Aires, Argentina; B, R. carpenteri (Thompson, 1873), male (41.7 × 33.9 mm) (NHM 1983.449), England; C, R. brevirostris (Doflein, 1904), male (15.8 × 11.4 mm) (ZRC 2011.1047), stn AT 89, 14 ° 59.74 ' S 166 ° 55.3 ' E, Vanuatu; D, R. pulchra (Miers, 1885), male (17.6 × 15.4 mm) (ZRC 2011.1043), stn CC 2746, 15 ° 58.78 ' N 121 ° 46.44 ' E, Luzon, Philippines; E, R. kotakae Takeda, 2001, male (13.4 × 17.2 mm) (ZRC 2011.1051), stn CP 2680, 14 ° 53.32 ' N 123 ° 14.40 ' E, Luzon, Philippines; F, R. fultoni, male (13.7 × 10.4 mm) (ZRC 2011.1057), stn CP 2832, 10 ° 44.54 ' S 162 ° 19.65 ' E, Solomon Islands." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/221767/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="363">
Fig. 
<number box="[214,228,188,213]" pageId="6" pageNumber="363" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
D). A fourth group of species has prominent lateral branchial spines with some tubercles on the carapace regions but otherwise smooth (e.g., 
<taxonomicName authority="Takeda, 2001" authorityName="Takeda" authorityYear="2001" box="[557,839,223,248]" class="Malacostraca" family="Epialtidae" genus="Rochinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="363" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kotakae">
<emphasis box="[557,676,224,248]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="363">R. kotakae</emphasis>
Takeda, 
<number box="[779,839,224,248]" pageId="6" pageNumber="363" value="2001.0">2001</number>
</taxonomicName>
), and while their male anterior thoracic sternums are transversely narrow with sternite 
<number box="[527,541,260,284]" pageId="6" pageNumber="363" value="4.0">4</number>
constricted, their male abdomens are acutely triangular (
<figureCitation box="[1180,1247,260,285]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1823,1845]" captionTargetBox="[182,1399,193,1793]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[182,1399,193,1793]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 5. Anterior thoracic sternums and abdomens of Rochinia species. A, R. gracilipes A. Milne-Edwards, 1875, male (15.8 × 11.2 mm) (USNM 1150573), Mar del Plata at breakwater, Buenos Aires, Argentina; B, R. carpenteri (Thompson, 1873), male (41.7 × 33.9 mm) (NHM 1983.449), England; C, R. brevirostris (Doflein, 1904), male (15.8 × 11.4 mm) (ZRC 2011.1047), stn AT 89, 14 ° 59.74 ' S 166 ° 55.3 ' E, Vanuatu; D, R. pulchra (Miers, 1885), male (17.6 × 15.4 mm) (ZRC 2011.1043), stn CC 2746, 15 ° 58.78 ' N 121 ° 46.44 ' E, Luzon, Philippines; E, R. kotakae Takeda, 2001, male (13.4 × 17.2 mm) (ZRC 2011.1051), stn CP 2680, 14 ° 53.32 ' N 123 ° 14.40 ' E, Luzon, Philippines; F, R. fultoni, male (13.7 × 10.4 mm) (ZRC 2011.1057), stn CP 2832, 10 ° 44.54 ' S 162 ° 19.65 ' E, Solomon Islands." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/221767/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="363">
Fig. 
<number box="[1233,1247,260,285]" pageId="6" pageNumber="363" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
E). A fifth group (e.g., 
<taxonomicName authority="Grant, 1905" authorityName="Grant" authorityYear="1905" box="[219,504,295,320]" class="Malacostraca" family="Epialtidae" genus="Rochinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="363" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fultoni">
<emphasis box="[219,327,296,320]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="363">R. fultoni</emphasis>
(Grant, 
<number box="[430,486,295,320]" pageId="6" pageNumber="363" value="1905.0">1905</number>
))
</taxonomicName>
has more elongated carapaces with distinct carapace regions and several sharp tubercles, and the male anterior thoracic sternum is transversely narrow and sternite 
<number box="[1165,1179,332,356]" pageId="6" pageNumber="363" value="4.0">4</number>
constricted, the male abdomen being acutely triangular (
<figureCitation box="[563,634,367,392]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1823,1845]" captionTargetBox="[182,1399,193,1793]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[182,1399,193,1793]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 5. Anterior thoracic sternums and abdomens of Rochinia species. A, R. gracilipes A. Milne-Edwards, 1875, male (15.8 × 11.2 mm) (USNM 1150573), Mar del Plata at breakwater, Buenos Aires, Argentina; B, R. carpenteri (Thompson, 1873), male (41.7 × 33.9 mm) (NHM 1983.449), England; C, R. brevirostris (Doflein, 1904), male (15.8 × 11.4 mm) (ZRC 2011.1047), stn AT 89, 14 ° 59.74 ' S 166 ° 55.3 ' E, Vanuatu; D, R. pulchra (Miers, 1885), male (17.6 × 15.4 mm) (ZRC 2011.1043), stn CC 2746, 15 ° 58.78 ' N 121 ° 46.44 ' E, Luzon, Philippines; E, R. kotakae Takeda, 2001, male (13.4 × 17.2 mm) (ZRC 2011.1051), stn CP 2680, 14 ° 53.32 ' N 123 ° 14.40 ' E, Luzon, Philippines; F, R. fultoni, male (13.7 × 10.4 mm) (ZRC 2011.1057), stn CP 2832, 10 ° 44.54 ' S 162 ° 19.65 ' E, Solomon Islands." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/221767/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="363">
Fig. 
<number box="[620,634,367,392]" pageId="6" pageNumber="363" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
F). Until all or most of the species are redescribed or re-examined, establishing new genera for each of these groups seems premature, especially because some characters may vary between species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,151,1149]" pageId="6" pageNumber="363">
<taxonomicName box="[199,444,476,500]" class="Malacostraca" family="Epialtidae" genus="Samadinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="363" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longispina" status="n. gen.">
<emphasis box="[199,444,476,500]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="363">Samadinia longispina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[453,611,476,501]" pageId="6" pageNumber="363">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[453,533,476,501]" pageId="6" pageNumber="363" rank="genus">n. gen.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, n. sp.
</emphasis>
is characterised by having a poorly defined regions of the dorsal surface of the carapace and by being covered with numerous small, rounded granules (
<figureCitation box="[1050,1124,511,536]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1942,1964]" captionTargetBox="[182,1407,193,1922]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[182,1408,193,1924]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Samadinia longispina n. gen., n. sp., holotype male (25.3 × 17.9 mm) (MNHN-IU- 2011 - 4190), French Polynesia, south of Society Islands. A, overall habitus; B, lateral view of carapace (lateral branchial spine broken); C, lateral-frontal view showing orbit and position of antennal flagellum." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/221763/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="363">
Figs. 
<number box="[1114,1124,512,536]" pageId="6" pageNumber="363" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
A, 
<number box="[1164,1177,512,536]" pageId="6" pageNumber="363" value="3.0">3</number>
A) (covered with large spines and/or sharp tubercles in 
<taxonomicName box="[519,620,548,572]" class="Malacostraca" family="Epialtidae" genus="Rochinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="363" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" sensu="lato">
<emphasis box="[519,620,548,572]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="363">Rochinia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[628,745,548,573]" pageId="6" pageNumber="363" sensu="lato">sensu lato</taxonomicNameLabel>
); the hepatic and lateral branchial spines are long, sharp and directed laterally (
<figureCitation box="[354,427,583,608]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1942,1964]" captionTargetBox="[182,1407,193,1922]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[182,1408,193,1924]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Samadinia longispina n. gen., n. sp., holotype male (25.3 × 17.9 mm) (MNHN-IU- 2011 - 4190), French Polynesia, south of Society Islands. A, overall habitus; B, lateral view of carapace (lateral branchial spine broken); C, lateral-frontal view showing orbit and position of antennal flagellum." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/221763/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="363">
Figs. 
<number box="[417,427,584,608]" pageId="6" pageNumber="363" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
A, 
<number box="[465,478,584,608]" pageId="6" pageNumber="363" value="3.0">3</number>
A) (carapace regions also with long spines in 
<taxonomicName box="[986,1087,584,608]" class="Malacostraca" family="Epialtidae" genus="Rochinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="363" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" sensu="lato">
<emphasis box="[986,1087,584,608]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="363">Rochinia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1094,1205,583,608]" pageId="6" pageNumber="363" sensu="lato">sensu lato</taxonomicNameLabel>
when this spines are long); the male anterior thoracic sternum is transversely conspicuously narrow, with sternite 
<number box="[1193,1207,620,644]" pageId="6" pageNumber="363" value="4.0">4</number>
strongly constricted anteriorly, with the anterolateral margins almost parallel and the median lateral margins strongly convex, forming a distinct structure (
<figureCitation box="[356,424,692,717]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1349,1371]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1327]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,193,1327]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Samadinia longispina n. gen., n. sp., holotype male (25.3 × 17.9 mm) (MNHN-IU- 2011 - 4190), French Polynesia. A, anterior thoracic sternum and abdomen; B, antennules, antennae and epistome; C, left third maxilliped; D, left chela." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/221764/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="363">
Fig. 
<number box="[410,424,692,716]" pageId="6" pageNumber="363" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
A) (relatively more constricted, with the lateral margins of the constricted portion almost parallel in 
<taxonomicName box="[282,402,728,752]" class="Malacostraca" family="Epialtidae" genus="Samadinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="363" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="n. gen.">
<emphasis box="[282,402,728,752]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="363">Samadinia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[414,498,727,752]" pageId="6" pageNumber="363" rank="genus">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[414,498,727,752]" pageId="6" pageNumber="363">n. gen.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
[
<figureCitation box="[518,592,727,752]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1349,1371]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1327]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,193,1327]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Samadinia longispina n. gen., n. sp., holotype male (25.3 × 17.9 mm) (MNHN-IU- 2011 - 4190), French Polynesia. A, anterior thoracic sternum and abdomen; B, antennules, antennae and epistome; C, left third maxilliped; D, left chela." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/221764/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="363">
Fig. 
<number box="[578,592,728,752]" pageId="6" pageNumber="363" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
A] but diverging in other 
<taxonomicName box="[907,1008,728,752]" class="Malacostraca" family="Epialtidae" genus="Rochinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="363" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[907,1008,728,752]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="363">Rochinia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species [
<figureCitation box="[1121,1194,727,752]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1823,1845]" captionTargetBox="[182,1399,193,1793]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[182,1399,193,1793]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 5. Anterior thoracic sternums and abdomens of Rochinia species. A, R. gracilipes A. Milne-Edwards, 1875, male (15.8 × 11.2 mm) (USNM 1150573), Mar del Plata at breakwater, Buenos Aires, Argentina; B, R. carpenteri (Thompson, 1873), male (41.7 × 33.9 mm) (NHM 1983.449), England; C, R. brevirostris (Doflein, 1904), male (15.8 × 11.4 mm) (ZRC 2011.1047), stn AT 89, 14 ° 59.74 ' S 166 ° 55.3 ' E, Vanuatu; D, R. pulchra (Miers, 1885), male (17.6 × 15.4 mm) (ZRC 2011.1043), stn CC 2746, 15 ° 58.78 ' N 121 ° 46.44 ' E, Luzon, Philippines; E, R. kotakae Takeda, 2001, male (13.4 × 17.2 mm) (ZRC 2011.1051), stn CP 2680, 14 ° 53.32 ' N 123 ° 14.40 ' E, Luzon, Philippines; F, R. fultoni, male (13.7 × 10.4 mm) (ZRC 2011.1057), stn CP 2832, 10 ° 44.54 ' S 162 ° 19.65 ' E, Solomon Islands." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/221767/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="363">
Fig. 
<number box="[1180,1194,727,752]" pageId="6" pageNumber="363" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
D?F]); and the male abdomen is broadly triangular, with somites 
<number box="[656,670,764,788]" pageId="6" pageNumber="363" value="3.0">3</number>
and 
<number box="[727,741,764,788]" pageId="6" pageNumber="363" value="4.0">4</number>
broadly trapezoidal and somites 
<number box="[1117,1131,764,789]" pageId="6" pageNumber="363" value="5.0">5</number>
and 
<number box="[1187,1201,764,789]" pageId="6" pageNumber="363" value="6.0">6</number>
subrectangular (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1349,1371]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1327]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,193,1327]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Samadinia longispina n. gen., n. sp., holotype male (25.3 × 17.9 mm) (MNHN-IU- 2011 - 4190), French Polynesia. A, anterior thoracic sternum and abdomen; B, antennules, antennae and epistome; C, left third maxilliped; D, left chela." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/221764/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="363">
Fig. 
<number box="[151,165,800,824]" pageId="6" pageNumber="363" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
A) (abdomen acutely triangular to T-shaped in 
<taxonomicName box="[704,805,800,824]" class="Malacostraca" family="Epialtidae" genus="Rochinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="363" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[704,805,800,824]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="363">Rochinia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, with somites 
<number box="[975,988,799,824]" pageId="6" pageNumber="363" value="3.0">3</number>
? 
<number box="[1000,1015,799,824]" pageId="6" pageNumber="363" value="6.0">6</number>
trapezoidal, with the condition most similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[266,427,836,860]" class="Malacostraca" family="Epialtidae" genus="Rochinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="363" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevirostris">
<emphasis box="[266,427,836,860]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="363">R. brevirostris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
[
<figureCitation box="[441,509,836,861]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1823,1845]" captionTargetBox="[182,1399,193,1793]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[182,1399,193,1793]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 5. Anterior thoracic sternums and abdomens of Rochinia species. A, R. gracilipes A. Milne-Edwards, 1875, male (15.8 × 11.2 mm) (USNM 1150573), Mar del Plata at breakwater, Buenos Aires, Argentina; B, R. carpenteri (Thompson, 1873), male (41.7 × 33.9 mm) (NHM 1983.449), England; C, R. brevirostris (Doflein, 1904), male (15.8 × 11.4 mm) (ZRC 2011.1047), stn AT 89, 14 ° 59.74 ' S 166 ° 55.3 ' E, Vanuatu; D, R. pulchra (Miers, 1885), male (17.6 × 15.4 mm) (ZRC 2011.1043), stn CC 2746, 15 ° 58.78 ' N 121 ° 46.44 ' E, Luzon, Philippines; E, R. kotakae Takeda, 2001, male (13.4 × 17.2 mm) (ZRC 2011.1051), stn CP 2680, 14 ° 53.32 ' N 123 ° 14.40 ' E, Luzon, Philippines; F, R. fultoni, male (13.7 × 10.4 mm) (ZRC 2011.1057), stn CP 2832, 10 ° 44.54 ' S 162 ° 19.65 ' E, Solomon Islands." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/221767/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="363">
Fig. 
<number box="[495,509,836,861]" pageId="6" pageNumber="363" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
C] but still relatively broader). This combination of characters is unique. No other species of 
<taxonomicName box="[271,372,872,896]" class="Malacostraca" family="Epialtidae" genus="Rochinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="363" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" sensu="lato">
<emphasis box="[271,372,872,896]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="363">Rochinia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[380,492,871,896]" pageId="6" pageNumber="363" sensu="lato">sensu lato</taxonomicNameLabel>
has the kind of dorsal carapace surface and very broad male abdomen present in 
<taxonomicName class="Malacostraca" family="Epialtidae" genus="Samadinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="363" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longispina" status="n. gen.">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="363">S. longispina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[279,443,908,933]" pageId="6" pageNumber="363">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[279,361,908,933]" pageId="6" pageNumber="363" rank="genus">n. gen.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, n. sp.
</emphasis>
As such, rather than placing it in 
<taxonomicName box="[846,947,908,932]" class="Malacostraca" family="Epialtidae" genus="Rochinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="363" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[846,947,908,932]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="363">Rochinia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and stretching the generic definition even further, it was felt that it was better to establish a separate genus for 
<taxonomicName box="[914,1060,944,968]" class="Malacostraca" family="Epialtidae" genus="Samadinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="363" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longispina" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[914,1060,944,968]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="363">S. longispina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1067,1130,943,968]" pageId="6" pageNumber="363" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1067,1130,943,968]" pageId="6" pageNumber="363">n. sp.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,151,1149]" pageId="6" pageNumber="363">
The new species of 
<taxonomicName box="[424,525,980,1004]" class="Malacostraca" family="Epialtidae" genus="Rochinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="363" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[424,525,980,1004]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="363">Rochinia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
described here, 
<taxonomicName box="[710,856,980,1004]" class="Malacostraca" family="Epialtidae" genus="Rochinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="363" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="granulosa" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[710,856,980,1004]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="363">R. granulosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[863,934,980,1005]" pageId="6" pageNumber="363">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[863,929,980,1005]" pageId="6" pageNumber="363" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
,
</emphasis>
also possesses a carapace that has relatively large granules covering the dorsal regions. The structure of these granules, however, is quite different, being relatively large and sub-fungiform rather than small and rounded. It also has a relatively broader male anterior thoracic sternum with a triangular male abdomen (
<figureCitation box="[733,825,1087,1112]" captionStart="FIGURE 3. A, E" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1769,1791]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,337,1746]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,337,1748]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 3. A, E, Samadinia longispina n. gen., n. sp., female (12.9 × 8.9 mm) (MNHN-IU- 2013 - 1678), New Caledonia; B- D, Rochinia granulosa n. sp., B, F, holotype female (9.7 × 6.7 mm) (MNHN-IU- 2011 - 2944 a), Papua New Guinea; C, D, paratype male (6.4 × 4.7 mm) (MNHN-IU- 2011 - 2944 b), Papua New Guinea. A-C, overall habitus; D, male anterior thoracic sternum and abdomen; E, F, female sterno-abdominal cavities and vulvae." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/221765/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="363">
Fig. 
<number box="[788,801,1088,1112]" pageId="6" pageNumber="363" value="3.0">3</number>
D
</figureCitation>
), more similar to that of 
<taxonomicName box="[1117,1219,1088,1112]" class="Malacostraca" family="Epialtidae" genus="Rochinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="363" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1117,1219,1088,1112]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="363">Rochinia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species such as 
<taxonomicName class="Malacostraca" family="Epialtidae" genus="Rochinia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="363" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevirostris">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="363">R. brevirostris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[295,362,1124,1149]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1823,1845]" captionTargetBox="[182,1399,193,1793]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[182,1399,193,1793]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 5. Anterior thoracic sternums and abdomens of Rochinia species. A, R. gracilipes A. Milne-Edwards, 1875, male (15.8 × 11.2 mm) (USNM 1150573), Mar del Plata at breakwater, Buenos Aires, Argentina; B, R. carpenteri (Thompson, 1873), male (41.7 × 33.9 mm) (NHM 1983.449), England; C, R. brevirostris (Doflein, 1904), male (15.8 × 11.4 mm) (ZRC 2011.1047), stn AT 89, 14 ° 59.74 ' S 166 ° 55.3 ' E, Vanuatu; D, R. pulchra (Miers, 1885), male (17.6 × 15.4 mm) (ZRC 2011.1043), stn CC 2746, 15 ° 58.78 ' N 121 ° 46.44 ' E, Luzon, Philippines; E, R. kotakae Takeda, 2001, male (13.4 × 17.2 mm) (ZRC 2011.1051), stn CP 2680, 14 ° 53.32 ' N 123 ° 14.40 ' E, Luzon, Philippines; F, R. fultoni, male (13.7 × 10.4 mm) (ZRC 2011.1057), stn CP 2832, 10 ° 44.54 ' S 162 ° 19.65 ' E, Solomon Islands." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/221767/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="363">
Fig. 
<number box="[347,362,1124,1149]" pageId="6" pageNumber="363" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
C).
</paragraph>
